FR940428-0-00050 FR940428-0-00020 Thursday April 28, 1994 Part VII Department of Transportation Federal Aviation Administration 14 CFR Part 25 Design Standards for Airplane Jacking and Tie-Down Provision; Final Rule Federal Register ␣/␣Vol. 59, No. 81␣/␣Thursday, April 28, 1994␣/␣Rules and Regulations DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION Federal Aviation Administration 14 CFR Part 25 [Docket No. 26129; Amdt. No. 25&hyph;81] RIN 2120&hyph;AD38 Design Standards for Airplane Jacking and Tie-Down Provisions AGENCY: Federal Aviation Administration, DOT. ACTION: Final rule. SUMMARY: This amendment to the airworthiness standards for transport category airplanes adds a new design standard for airplane jacking and tie-down provisions. This amendment is needed to provide manufacturers with design standards for jacking conditions and is intended to protect primary airplane structure during jacking operations and from gusty wind conditions while tied down. EFFECTIVE DATE: May 31, 1994. FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: Iven Connally, FAA, Airframe and Propulsion Branch (ANM&hyph;112), Transport Airplane Directorate, Aircraft Certification Service, 1601 Lind Avenue SW, Renton, WA 98055&hyph;4056; telephone (206) 227&hyph;2120. SUPPLEMENTARY INFORMATION: Background This amendment is based on Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (NPRM) 90&hyph;3, which was published in the Federal Register on February 9, 1990 (55 FR 4790). The notice was predicated on a need to protect primary airplane structure from damage during jacking operations and during gusty wind conditions.
